Narrative:
On May [XXX], 2025 at 10:38 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a heavy truck on [XXX] near [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was traveling westbound on [XXX]. The heavy truck traveling eastbound on [XXX] began maneuvering left into the path of the Waymo AV and the Waymo AV came to a stop. The truck continued and the front driver side of the heavy truck made contact with the front driver side of the Waymo AV. The heavy truck then reversed and proceeded eastbound. As the heavy truck passed the stationary Waymo AV, it made contact with the driver side of the stationary Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vehicle involved was towed away. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On April [XXX], 2025 at 7:44 AM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a heavy truck on [XXX] near [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was stopped facing southeast on [XXX], yielding to a heavy truck traveling northwest in a narrow roadway with parked vehicles on both sides of the street. As the heavy truck passed the stopped Waymo AV, the driver side of the heavy truck cab made contact with the rear driver side of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On April [XXX], 2025 at 2:40 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Santa Monica, California was in a collision involving a heavy truck on [XXX] near [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was parked in-lane facing northwest on a narrow portion of [XXX], with hazard lights activated, when a heavy truck traveling southeastbound on [XXX] passed the Waymo AV on the right. As the heavy truck passed by the stationary Waymo AV, the passenger side of the heavy truck trailer made contact with the rear passenger side of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage.

On May [XXX], 2025 at 9:59 AM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Los Angeles, California was in a collision involving a box truck and trailer on [XXX] at [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was traveling southeastbound on [XXX] in the leftmost lane when it stopped at the intersection of [XXX] to yield to a box truck hauling a trailer within the intersection. The heavy truck was facing southwest, apparently attempting a multi-point turn. The truck stopped and the Waymo AV began to pass the truck on the left. The truck began reversing as the Waymo AV was passing and the Waymo AV came to a stop to yield to the truck. While the Waymo AV remained stopped, the truck continued to reverse, and the rear passenger side of the trailer made contact with the front passenger side of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vehicle involved was towed away. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On May [XXX], 2025 at 7:06 AM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Los Angeles, California was in a collision involving a heavy truck on [XXX] near [XXX].

At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage.

On May [XXX], 2025 at 7:44 AM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a heavy truck on [XXX] at [XXX].

On April [XXX], 2025 at 6:34 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Los Angeles, California was in a collision involving a heavy truck on [XXX] near [XXX].

The passengers in the Waymo AV were not belted at the time of the collision, as they were preparing to exit the Waymo AV. The Waymo AV sustained damage.

On March [XXX] at approximately 2:20 PM CT, the passenger-side mirror of a lifted Ford F-350 with dual rear wheels made light contact with a Kodiak Driver-equipped autonomous trucks drivers side mirror. On February [XXX]at 7:08 PM CT, a tractor-trailer encroached into the lane of a Kodiak Driver-equipped autonomous truck traveling Northbound on [XXX]in Thackerville, Oklahoma. On December [XXX], 2024 at 1:08 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a heavy truck on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was in autonomous mode traveling north in the rightmost of two lanes on [XXX] when it partially entered the left adjacent lane to make room for a cyclist on its right who was traveling in the same direction.  A heavy truck behind in the left adjacent lane proceeded forward, and the Waymo AV test driver transitioned to manual mode immediately before the rear driver side of the Waymo AV made contact with the front passenger side of the heavy truck.  At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was not engaged and a test driver was operating the Waymo AV in manual mode.  Both vehicles sustained damage.
Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vulnerable road user influenced the driving task of a vehicle involved and a vehicle involved was towed away.  Transdev may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.  This is a duplicate of NHTSA ID: 30270-9454-1.

On December 13, 2024, GM Cruise Holdings LLC ("Cruise") filed an Incident Report (the "Report") under the Second Amended Standing General Order 2021-01, dated April 5, 2023 (the "Order") General Motors LLC (GM) manufactured the Cruise-operated motor vehicle involved in the incident summarized in the Incident Report. Because GM is also a Reporting Entity under the Order, GM is submitting a duplicate of the redacted public copy of the Report. GM has selected "Unknown" in the "ADS version" and "ODD time" fields solely to avoid a second submission of nonpublic Cruise CBI GM is in possession of Cruise's responses to these fields and incorporates Cruise's responses into this submission by reference. GM's submission is based on facts supplied to GM by Cruise. GM has not investigated the alleged incident and currently believes, based on a reasonable inquiry, that it has no independent knowledge of the facts in the Report. (Reference file: 30412-9268-1).

On November [XXX], 2024, at 9:10am CST, a Cruise autonomous vehicle ("AV") operating in supervised autonomous mode in Houston, Texas was traveling westbound on [XXX] between [XXX] and [XXX]. The AV came to a complete stop behind a semi-trailer truck stopped at a traffic signal at the intersection with [XXX]. The semi-trailer truck reversed into the AV, making contact with the front of the AV twice. Prior to contact, the AV operator honked the horn to attempt to alert the truck driver After contact, the AV operator got out of the car to attempt to flag down the truck driver. However, the driver of the semi-trailer truck left the scene without exchanging information. The impact resulted in damage to the front end of the AV. The AV was driven away from the scene, and a police report was filed to document the incident. The AV operator later reported moderate injuries.

On November [XXX], 2024 at 8:39 AM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a heavy truck on [XXX] at [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was stopped at a red light in the second lane from the left of five one-way lanes facing north on [XXX] at the intersection with [XXX] when a heavy truck came to a stop alongside the AV on the left, positioned partially within the AV's lane.  The light turned green and the AV remained stopped due to the very close proximity with the heavy truck within its lane to the left, and the heavy truck initiated a left turn. As the heavy truck turned, the rear passenger side corner of the heavy truck swung even further into the AV's lane and made contact with the driver side of the Waymo AV.  At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vehicle involved was towed away. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

This incident occurred near Streetman, TX on [XXX] at approximately 3:03 PM CT on February [XXX], 2024. The Aurora vehicle was operating in autonomy at the time. Conditions were clear. As the Aurora vehicle was driving in its lane at 62 mph, a box truck veered into the lane of the Aurora vehicle. The box truck's mirror appeared to make contact with the back of the trailer that the Aurora Driver was pulling. At this time, we are not aware of any injuries, and camera footage appears to show that the box truck continued to drive. From the post-trip inspection, there was not any visible trailer damage. Before the collision, the Aurora Driver was driving straight in its lane and passing the box truck. Shortly thereafter, the box truck began to encroach into the lane of the Aurora Driver. The Aurora Driver detected the box truck's encroachment into the Aurora vehicle's lane and initiated a nudge away from the box truck to provide space. The Aurora Driver detected the collision and made the decision to initiate an incident response, but before it could execute that response, the Vehicle Operator took over control of the system and proceeded in manual. The Aurora vehicle then re-engaged in autonomy approximately two minutes later. 
The Vehicle Operator did not visually observe the collision, assumed the reaction of the Aurora Driver to be a software anomaly, and reported the vehicle nudge through the standard annotation protocol rather than through the incident response protocols. The incident was identified at approximately 1:03 PM CT on February 2, 2024, through a review of Aurora's data logs.

On August [XXX], 2023 at 9:54 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a heavy truck on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling northbound on [XXX] when it approached a heavy truck and trailer that was stopped in the adjacent lane on the left side of the street. As the Waymo began to slowly pass the truck, the truck initiated a reversing turn maneuver into a loading bay on the left side of [XXX]. The Waymo AV then came to a stop, and as the Waymo AV was initiating its own reversing maneuver to clear the path for the truck, the right side of the trailer made contact with the front driver's side corner of the Waymo AV. Operating Entity: Mercedes-Benz Research and Development North America
Narrative: Mercedes-Benz has conducted a review of the incident and the following is based on that review. The subject Mercedes-Benz Drive Pilot test vehicle was traveling between 15-20 mph in the #2 northbound lane on the [XXX] in California in stop and go traffic with the L3 ADS activated by the driver. The vehicle's ADS determined that a truck traveling in the adjacent lane had a trajectory towards the Drive Pilot's lane, and so the Mercedes-Benz test vehicle autonomously applied the brakes to avoid a collision. After applying the brakes and bringing itself to a standstill, the Mercedes-Benz was then struck in the rear bumper by a trailing semi-truck that did not stop in time. No injuries were reported, no airbags deployed in either vehicle, and both vehicles were able to be driven from the scene of the incident. The Mercedes-Benz vehicle experienced minor damage to the rear bumper, and no damage was observed on the semi-truck at the scene. The CA Traffic Collision Report for the subject incident noted a violation of California Vehicle Code 22350 (unsafe speed for traffic conditions) by the semi-truck in the #2 lane that struck the rear bumper of the Mercedes-Benz.

The Waymo AV was traveling straight in autonomous mode in the leftmost lane, when the test driver took manual control and attempted a right lane change. As the test driver prepared to make the lane change, there was a Class 8 semi-truck and flat-bed trailer passing in the adjacent right lane. As the Waymo AV test driver initiated the lane change, the Waymo AV made contact with the rear corner of the flat-bed trailer. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AVs Level 4 ADS was not engaged and a test driver was operating the Waymo AV in manual mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage. Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Transdev may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available. This report is a duplicate of WaymoLLC-20221216-0 (rev.20230117160244).

On November [XXX], 2022 at 8:48 AM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in Phoenix, Arizona was in a collision involving a garbage truck on the 500 block of [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling eastbound on [XXX] when it encountered a stopped garbage truck traveling westbound. The Waymo AV pulled to the right side of the street and stopped, unable to proceed past the garbage truck and an SUV parked parallel to the curb. The garbage truck then attempted to pass between the Waymo AV and a parked passenger vehicle to the right of the garbage truck, and the garbage truck made contact with the left rear corner of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AVs Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode and the Waymo AV was stationary. The Waymo AV sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On August [XXX], 2022 at 6:33 PM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") Peterbilt Class 8 semi-truck and trailer, operating in Ennis, Texas was in a collision involving a Class 8 semi-truck and trailer on northbound [XXX] near [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling in autonomous mode in the middle lane on [XXX] when a Class 8 semi-truck and trailer began to pass it in the adjacent left lane.  Before the adjacent Class 8 semi-truck and trailer had fully passed the Waymo AV, it began to execute a right lane change and its trailer (the right side, rear section) entered the lane in which the Waymo AV was traveling and made contact with the driver side of the Waymo AV cab.  The Waymo AV transitioned to manual mode and the test driver took control.  At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present (in the driver's seating position).  The Waymo AV sustained damage and the third-party Class 8 semi-truck and trailer did not stop to exchange information.
Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01.  Transdev may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.  This report is a duplicate of WaymoLLC-202208[XXX]-0 (rev. 2022019[XXX]185808)

No injuries were reported and the contact from the truck resulted in two minor scratches and two indentations on the rear bumper of the Mercedes-Benz.  The driver of the truck did not pull over after the collision. The Mercedes-Benz was driven from the incident location, and further inspection of the vehicle concluded no additional damage beyond the cosmetic dents and surface scratches.

On May [XXX], 2022 at 3:11 PM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) Peterbilt Class 8 semi-truck and trailer, operating in Ennis, Texas was in a collision involving a Class 8 semi-truck and trailer on northbound [XXX] near [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was traveling in autonomous mode in the rightmost lane on Interstate [XXX] when a Class 8 semi-truck and trailer began to pass it in the adjacent left lane. Before the adjacent Class 8 semi-truck and trailer had fully passed the Waymo AV, it executed a right lane change and its trailer (the right side, rear section) entered the lane in which the Waymo AV was traveling and made contact with the driver side of the Waymo AV cab. The Waymo AV transitioned to manual mode and the test driver took control. The Waymo AV exited the roadway to the right shoulder of the road and came to a stop off of the roadway. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present (in the driver's seating position). The Waymo AV sustained moderate damage and the third-party Class 8 semi-truck and trailer did not stop to exchange information. The Waymo AV test driver was transported for medical care and the Waymo AV software operator, seated in the passenger seat, later sought medical attention. 
Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because an individual involved in the crash was transported from the scene to a hospital for medical treatment and a vehicle involved was towed away. Transdev may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available. 
This report is identical to WaymoLLC-202205[XXX]-0 (rev.202205[XXX]603622)

On February [XXX], 2022 at 10:30 AM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ('Waymo AV') Peterbilt Class 8 semi-truck and trailer, operating in Gila River, AZ was in a collision involving a box truck on [XXX] south of [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was traveling southbound on [XXX] in autonomous mode in the right lane, and a motor coach followed by a box truck were traveling in the adjacent left lane. Traffic in the left lane began to slow and the box truck steered to the right and crossed into the right lane before making contact with the passenger side rear corner of the motor coach and then making contact with the driver side rear axle of the Waymo AV trailer. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV was in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present (in the driver's seating position). The Waymo AV trailer, motor coach, and box truck sustained damage. 
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vehicle involved was towed away. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available. This report was submitted from the Pacific time zone on the required date.
